{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512692"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11937"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11937"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.05,0.42,0.15,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4533"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44933"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4533"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11937"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29835"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43282"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44933"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old\u00a0woman presents to her General Practitioner with a three-week history of generalised weakness, fatigue, and malaise. She denies fever, cough, rash, and recent travel. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medication. She is a non-smoker and does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her vital signs are within normal limits. Physical examination reveals 4/5 strength in the hip flexors and abductors of the shoulders bilaterally; the other muscle groups tested have normal (5/5) power. The rest of\u00a0the\u00a0examination is unremarkable and in particular, there is no rash and auscultation of the chest is clear. Laboratory workup shows a normal full blood examination and creatinine.\u00a0The aspartate aminotransferase level (AST) is 230 U/L (normal \u0026lt;45), alanine aminotransferase level (ALT) is 105 U/L (normal \u0026lt;50), gamma glutamyl transpeptidase (GGT) is 35 U/L (\u0026lt;60) and alkaline phosphatase (ALP) is 50 U/L (30-110). Total bilirubin is 15umol/L (\u0026lt;20), and albumin levels are 40g/L (35-50). Serology for hepatitis B and C is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal ultrasound","Liver biopsy","Serum creatine kinase","Proximal muscle biopsy","Thyroid autoantibodies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has evidence of bilateral proximal muscle weakness, raising suspicion of idiopathic inflammatory myopathy. The next step in evaluating this patient is measuring serum muscle enzymes (\u003Cstrong\u003Eserum\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ecreatine kinase \u003C/strong\u003E(CK) and/or aldolase), and if elevated, followed by an autoantibody testing for myositis-specific and myositis-associated antibodies (MSAs and MAAs), electromyogram or nerve conduction study, as well as an MRI of the thighs to identify features of myositis and guide muscle biopsy. While a \u003Cstrong\u003Eproximal\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Emuscle biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Eis likely to be a reasonable investigation, it would not be the next best step, as the above investigations should occur first (e.g. serum CK, autoantibody testing).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypothyroidism is a reasonable differential in a patient presenting with generalised weakness, fatigue and malaise. However, the patient has no other symptoms of hypothyroidism (e.g. sensitivity to cold, constipation, low mood) and her LFTs suggest an alternative pathology. Thyroid function tests (e.g. TSH) would be requested initially, and if abnormal, then thyroid autoantibodies would be requested if appropriate. Thus, \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid autoantibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are not the next most appropriate investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe LFTs demonstrate a hepatitic picture with a normal GGT and ALP, and occur in the context of her proximal muscle weakness and absence of hepatitis risk factors and she tested negative for Hepatitis B and C. As such, a liver pathology is less likely, and it is most probable that her LFTs are due to an extra-hepatic pathology (e.g. muscle breakdown), thus \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect. In the same vein, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be performed before imaging of the liver, and in the absence of a suspected liver pathology, it is not the next best diagnostic step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Although commonly referred to as liver function tests, aspartate and alanine aminotransferase (AST and ALT) can also arise from extra-hepatic sources such as muscle, and should raise the suspicion of an idiopathic inflammatory myopathy in the setting of proximal weakness with an isolated increase in these enzymes."],"references":["Malik A, Hayat G, Kalia JS, Guzman MA. Idiopathic Inflammatory Myopathies: Clinical Approach and Management. Front Neurol. 2016;7:64. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27242652/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29835"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11937"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29835"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-09T13:54:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-09T13:54:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4533"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44933"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2560"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Paraplegia","synonyms":["Weakness","Proximal muscle weakness"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-07-11T23:00:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T11:46:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4061"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Liver function tests"